---

# 2) DSL v1 grammar (EBNF)

This grammar is intentionally minimal and line-friendly.

## 2.1 Lexical tokens

```ebnf
identifier  = letter , { letter | digit | "_" } ;
integer     = [ "-" ] , digit , { digit } ;
float       = [ "-" ] , digit , { digit } , "." , digit , { digit } ;
number      = float | integer ;
string      = '"' , { character - '"' } , '"' ;

ws          = { " " | "\t" } ;
newline     = "\r\n" | "\n" ;
comment     = "#" , { character - newline } ;
```

## 2.2 Grammar

```ebnf
file        = { ws , ( statement | comment ) , ws , newline } ;

statement   = graph_decl
            | graph_end
            | io_decl
            | node_decl
            | connect_stmt ;

graph_decl  = "graph" , ws , string ;
graph_end   = "end" ;

io_decl     = "io" , ws , ( "input" | "output" ) , ws ,
              identifier , ws , ":" , ws , format_spec ;

format_spec = sample_fmt , "@" , integer , "k" ,
              ws , "block" , "=" , integer ,
              ws , "ch" , "=" , integer ;

sample_fmt  = "f32" | "s16" ;

node_decl   = "node" , ws , identifier , ws , ":" , ws , identifier ,
              [ ws , "(" , ws , param_list , ws , ")" ] ;

param_list  = param , { ws , "," , ws , param } ;
param       = identifier , ws , "=" , ws , value ;
value       = number | string ;

connect_stmt= "connect" , ws , endpoint , ws , "->" , ws , endpoint ;

endpoint    = identifier , [ "." , identifier ] ;
```

Notes:

* `endpoint` allows `mic` or `eq.in`. For IO identifiers without `.pin`, the tool can treat them as default pin (e.g., `out` or `in`) by convention.
* Module class name is the second identifier in `node_decl` (e.g., `Gain`, `Biquad`).
* Params are key/value; values are numbers or strings.

